This notebook sets out to document the demographic differences between the California Community College (CCC), the California State University (CSU), and the University of California (UC) systems, particularly when it comes to gender, ethnicity, and age, and to see how these differences have changed from 2010 and 2015 to 2021. Unfortunately, the UC did not provide age demographics, so we will only focus on gender and ethnicity for the UC system.

I chose this topic to document the changing demographics of the different California college systems, especially as overall demographics have changed, and to see what differences there may be among the different systems.

The input data is all data provided through the official CCC, CSU, and UC sources:

CCC: https://datamart.cccco.edu/students/Student_Term_Annual_Count.aspx

CSU: https://tableau.calstate.edu/views/SelfEnrollmentDashboard/EnrollmentSummary?iframeSizedToWindow=true&%3Aembed=y&%3AshowAppBanner=false&%3Adisplay_count=no&%3AshowVizHome=no

UC: https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/about-us/information-center/fall-enrollment-glance

CCC files were downloaded as CSV files, CSU and UC files were more easily read in as .xlsx files.

As this is only a data analysis notebook, our main modules will be Pandas, Numpy, and matplotlib.

3) Now that we have our data frames settled, we can finally start conducting our analysis. We will look at each demographic area first (ethnicity, gender, and age) and see how they change from 2010 to 2015 to 2021

3a) First, we start by graphing the ethnicity distribution in 2010 for each system.

In [273]:
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4, wspace=0.4)

cccEth = commEth.groupby("ethnicity").sum()
cccEth = cccEth.sort_values(by="2010Count")
plt.title("2010 CCC Student Distribution by Ethnicity", fontsize=12)
plt.bar(np.arange(len(cccEth.index)), cccEth["2010Count"], align="center")
plt.xticks(np.arange(len(cccEth.index)), cccEth.index.values, rotation=90, fontsize=12)


csuEth = csuEthDF[csuEthDF.year == 2010]
csuEth = csuEth.groupby("ethnicity").sum()
csuEth = csuEth.sort_values(by="records")
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
plt.title("2010 CSU Student Distribution by Ethnicity")
plt.bar(np.arange(len(csuEth.index)), csuEth["records"], align="center")
plt.xticks(np.arange(len(csuEth.index)), csuEth.index.values, rotation=90, fontsize=12)


ucEth = ucDFEth.groupby("Categories").sum()
ucEth = ucEth.sort_values(by="2010")
ucEth = ucEth.drop("Total")
plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
plt.title("2010 UC Student Distribution by Ethnicity")
plt.bar(np.arange(len(ucEth.index)), ucEth["2010"], align="center")
plt.xticks(np.arange(len(ucEth.index)), ucEth.index.values, rotation=90, fontsize=12)
plt.show()

We can see that in 2010, the CCC system and CSU system were similar in that their students largely identified as White or Hispanic. The UC System, meanwhile, was mainly White and Asian. In all three cases, Hispanic/Latino, White, and Asian were still the top 3 ethnicities. Additionally, "American Indians" and "Pacific Islanders" were consistently the least-represented ethnicities in all three systems.

Conclusion This conclusion will be broken up into four parts: one for each year, and then a final part to summarize the findings.

Demographic Differences in 2010

Ethnicity

In 2010, there are a fair few commonalities between the three systems. For example, in all three systems, the top represented demographics are consistently Hispanic/Latino, White Non-Hispanic, and Asian. However, while the CCC system has a Hispanic majority at 34%, the CSU and UC systems both have white majorities, with 33.71% and 33.15%, respectively.

Additionally, all three systems also have the same two least-represented ethnicities, with that being American Indian and Pacific Islander. Interestingly enough, however, the CCC system lists "Filipino" as a separate Ethnic group, whereas the CSU and UC systems do not, so the CSU and UC systems' inclusion of "Filipino" into one of the other ethnic categories may have a distinct effect on these percentages. Additionally, the CCC system does not include a separate "international" category whereas the CSU and UC system do, which may effect this data.

In 2010, it is also interesting to note that while the CCC and CSU systems have similar African American populations, at 7.33% and 5% respectively, the UC system has significantly less, with only 3.41% of their population being African American.

Gender

In 2010, all three systems share the fact that the majority of their demographics are Female as opposed to Male. Of note, however, is the fact that in 2010, the CCC and UC system both allowed for an "Unknown" or "Not reported" category. This category is around 1.29% in for the CCC and about 0.13% in the UC system, and the CSU system did not include an equivalent category, which may affect the data.

Additionally, the CSU system had the greatest difference in gender. They had a female percentage of 57.43%, as opposed to the CCC system's 53.79% and the UC system's 51.66%, which is a difference of at least 3.64%, which is a noticeable difference.

Age

In 2010, the CCC system had a significantly younger demographic than the CSU system. 24.16% of the CCC system's students were aged 19 or less, as compared to the CSU's equivalent of around 20.92%. Additionally, 30.01% of the CCC's system were aged 20-24. The CSU system's equivalent categories sum to around 49.49%, meaning the CSU has a significantly higher portion of students in the 20-24 age range than the CCC system.

Interestingly enough, while the CCC system has more of a younger demographic than the CSU system, it also has more of an older demographic. For example, the CCC system had a total of 10.67% for the 50+ age range, while the CSU's equivalent had only a 1.89%. This same pattern can be seen in the 30-34, 35-39, and 40-49 age range, for which the CCC system has 7.70%, 5.58%, and 8.85%, respectively, while the CSU system has significantly less, with respective percentages of 5.64%, 2.76% and 3.24%.

Demographic Differences in 2015

Ethnicity

In 2015, there are a few notable patterns across all three systems. The first is the encreased Hispanic enrollment; the Hispanic population froms from 34% to 43.77% in the CCC system, from 27.3% to 36.94% in the CSUs, and from 15.35 to 19.29% in the UCs. This is accompanied by a universal decrease in White enrollment, from 32.23% to 27.12% for the CCCs, from 33.71% to 25.77% in the CSUs, and from 33.15% to 26.94% in the UCs. This also means that the the Hispanic population for the CCC and CSU systems are now the most-represented ethnic groups in 2015, and Asians now become the most-represented group in the UC system. However, the Hispanic, White, and Asian groups remain the top-3 ethnic groups in each system in 2015.

Those are the most notable ethnicity changes from 2010, but some other details should be pointed out. For one, the CCC and CSu systems both see a decrease in African American, American Indian, and Pacific Islander enrollment. The UC system, on the other hand, remains relatively steady in these enrollment rates, although they have tehe lowest enrollment rates for all three aforementioned ethnicities of the three college systems.

It is also interesting to note that all three systems see a decrease in the "Unknown" ethnic category from 2010 to 2015, and they all have similar "Unknown" percentages, hovering between 4-5% for all three systems.

Gender

The patterns seen in 2010 remain consistent in 2015, with all three systems having a majority female demographic. In fact, there is not much change to be seen here, except for a minor decrease in the CSU female demographic from 57.43% to 56.07%. however, the other systems remain consistent in their percentage points.

One feature of note is the fact that in 2015, the CCC system sees a decrease in the "unknown" category to 1.07%, while the UC system sees an increase to 0.16%, although both categories remain a minority in their respective systems.

Age

In 2015, the age demographics follow a similar pattern as 2010. The CCC system continues to have more younger and more older students, while the CSUs main student population falls largely in between the 20-24 age range. However, there are a few things of note. For one, the CCC system has gone from 30.01% to 33.03% for their 20-24 age range, while seeing a related decrease in the 40-49 and 50+ age ranges, from 8.85% to 6.83% and 10.67% to 8.82%, respectively. In the same token, the CSU system sees an increase in their under-19 age range, with a total of 23.23%, as opposed to 20.92% in 2010. Thus, to some degree, the CCC and CSU systems have grown slightly more simliar in their age demographic ranges.

Demographic Differences in 2021

Ethnicity Patterns seen in ethnicity in 2015 remain largely the same in 2021. The CCC and CSU systems continue to have majority Hispanic/Latino populations, followed closely by White, and then Asian. The UC system also remains quite similar, with a majority Asian demographic, followed by White, then Hispanic/Latino.

It is worth noting, however, that the Hispanic growth pattern seen going from 2010 to 2015 continues in 2021, with Hispanics now making up 47.49% of 2021 CCC students, 45.38% of CSU students, and 21.97% in UC students. This coincides with the White enrollment dropping to 24%, 21.54%, and 22.22% for the CCC, CSU, and UC systems.

Broadly speaking, the Hispanic, Latino, and Asian ethnic groups remain the top three ethnic groups enrolled in these systems. The least-represented ethnic groups also remain the same. American Indian enrollment sees a decrease across all three systems, even in the UC system, which had remained steady in 2015. Pacific Islander enrollment has increased in 2021 for the UC system compared to 2015, although they still haven't reached the same levels as 2010. A similar pattern can be seen in the CSU system.

Additionally, the UC system has a significant amount of international students, sitting at around 15.11%, as opposed to only 5.24% of CSU students, and the CCC system still lacks this data in 2021. The CCC and CSU systems also have similar multi-ethnic percentages of 4.31% and 4.20%, respectively, whilee the UC system does not track this information.

Gender 2021 is the first year in which the UC system began offering gender options beyond Male, Female, and Not Reported, and the first year in which the CCC system began offering Non-Binary as an option, which are significant changes that may affect this analysis.

Moving forward, all three systems maintain a majority-female student demographic, with only minor changes from previous years. Most notably are the aforementioned additions to the gender system. Also the CSU system does not offer any new options, the CCC system reports that 0.24% of its students are Non-Binary, while 1.48% are unknown. The equivalent categories for the UC system sit at, respectively, 0.11% and 0.79%, so the CCC system continues to have a greater amount of Non-Binary and Unknown Gender students. However, the UC system also offers options for Trans Female and Trans Male, which could impact the percentage of "Female" and "Male," especially depending on how these options are categorized in the CCC system.

Age In 2021, the CCC system has a massive jump in the "19 or less" age category, sitting at 31.94%, compared to 24.99% in 2015. The CSU system sees a similar increase, with 1.62% of its students being categorized as under 18, or about 4x the 2015 percentage of 0.45. This also means the CSU sytem has a combined "19 or less" percentage of about 24.28%, which is increase that follows the pattern of previous years.

Accompanying this increase in the CCC system is a notable decrease in the 20-24 age range, with a percentage of 27.89%, as opposed to 33.03%. For the CSU system, their 20-24 age range remains about the same as previous years, at about 49.91%. What's interesting, however, is that where iin previous years, their 20-21 age range was less than their 22-24 age range, this pattern has reversed in 2021, with 27% of their students falling into the 20-21 age range and 23.91% of their students falling into the 22-24 age range.

Additionally, the CCC system maintains a higher older demographic than the CSU system, with 35-39, 40-49, and 50+ percentages of 5.54%, 6.64%, and 7.24%, respectively, while the CSU system's equivalents sit comparatively lower at 2.37%, 2.16%, and 0.96%.

Summary of Analysis

Ethnicity

Across all three systems, Hispanic/Latinos, White Non-Hispanics, and Asians were consistently the most represented ethnicities for all three systems. However, over time, the emphasis shifted from White Non-Hispanics to Hispanic/Latinos, with Asians remaining relatively consistent. Initially, both CSU and UC systems had a White majority, with the CCC system being the only exception with a Hispanic majority in 2010. By 2021, however, the CCC and CSU systems both had Hispanic/Latino majorities, with the UC system having Asians as the most-represented ethnicity. By 2021, the White ethnic group was the least-represented of these three ethnic groups, although Pacific Islanders and American Indians remained the least-represented ethnic groups for all systems across all three years.

Gender

All three systems were very similar in that their demographics were majority female, although the extent varied between systems. This commonality remained consistent throughout all three years, even with the addition of a "Non-Binary" option for the CCC system and the "Non-Binary", "Genderqueer," and "Trans Male" and "Trans Female" categories in 2021.

Age

The CCC system consistently maintained a larger younger and a larger older demographic than the CSU system throughout every year, although the CSU system had a much more prominent middle demographic. Broadly speaking, the CSU and CCC systems both skewed younger, with their demographics generally falling under the age of 24, although, as previously mentioned, the CCC system had a notable portion of its student base above the age of 35.

To improve this result, it may be worthwhile to, in the future, also look at general California demographic data. That way, we can not only compare the demographic data between the different college systems, but we could also compare it to the general California population, and to see how changes in California's demographics are reflected in the college systems.
